# Pull Request Creation Standards

When the user asks to create a Pull Request (PR), you must follow this standard structure for the PR title and body. Use the `gh` CLI tool via the `Shell` tool to create the PR.

## 1. Title Format
Use the format: `Type: Short Description`
Examples:
- `Feature: Organization-Specific Call Rates`
- `Bugfix: Fix scheduling delay calculation`
- `Refactor: Update Google Cloud client initialization`

## 2. Body Structure
The body MUST use the following markdown template. Ensure you fill in the sections based on the actual changes (use `git status`, `git diff`, and `git log` to analyze changes first).

```markdown
## Description
[A comprehensive high-level summary of what this PR achieves. Explain the "why" and the "what".]

## Technical Description
[Detailed breakdown of technical changes, grouped by component or area. Use bullet points.]

### [Area/Component Name]
- **[Specific Change]:** [Details]
- **[Specific Change]:** [Details]

## Related Issue
[Issue number linked, e.g., #123, or "NA"]

## Type of Change
- [ ] Bug fix
- [ ] New feature
- [ ] Breaking change
- [ ] Refactor
- [ ] Documentation update
- [ ] Other: [Description]

## Breaking Changes
[Explain any breaking changes or state "None". If there are breaking changes, explain how to mitigate them.]

## Testing
[List the tests added or run to verify the changes.]
- [ ] [Test description, e.g., "Added unit tests for X"]
- [ ] [Test description, e.g., "Verified admin interface manually"]
```

## 3. Command Execution
Use the `gh pr create` command with a HEREDOC for the body to ensure proper formatting.

Example:
```bash
gh pr create --title "Type: Title" --body "$(cat <<'EOF'
## Description
...
EOF
)"
```
